  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Silk Is Beautiful and It Tangles" imageAlt="Yorkshire Terrier puppy having its silky coat combed" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Yorkie coat behaves like fine human hair: it barely sheds, and it tangles for a living. Kept long it needs daily combing and a genuine commitment; kept in the sensible puppy cut, which is what nearly every Singapore Yorkie wears, it needs a comb-through 2 to 3 times a week and a salon trim every 4 to 6 weeks.</p>
      <p>The daily ten-second habits: a face check to keep hair out of the eyes (or the classic topknot if you keep it longer), and the tooth-brushing routine, which for this breed matters more than any coat care; more on that below. All the starting tools are in your kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Yorkie Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Yorkshire Terrier puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Yorkshire Terrier goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Yorkie health points worth knowing: dental disease is the breed's biggest lifelong issue, a tiny jaw crowds teeth badly, so brushing starts day one, not after the first bad vet visit; tracheal collapse, the toy-breed windpipe weakness, which is why the harness rule is absolute; patellar luxation, the small-breed kneecap issue; and in very young puppies, low blood sugar, which regular small meals prevent.</p>
      <p>Worth asking any seller about: liver shunt (portosystemic shunt) appears in Yorkie lines more than most breeds, and a proper vet check catches the signs early. Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the puppy health checks explained guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="The Truth About Teacup Yorkies" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>The Yorkie sits near the top of every "teacup" price list in Singapore, because the breed is already tiny and the market rewards "even tinier". We don't sell to that label. Dogs bred to be unusually small carry higher risks: fragile bones, worse dental crowding, collapsing tracheas, chronic low blood sugar, and shorter lives.</p>
      <p>A healthy Yorkie at 2 to 3.5 kg already travels in a tote bag and naps in a shoebox. If a seller guarantees an adult weight below that range, treat the promise as a warning, not a feature.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Teacup red flags</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'Guaranteed adult weight below 2 kg',
            'No mention of the parents\' actual size',
            '"Teacup" or "micro" priced at a premium',
          ].map((fact) => (
            <li class="flex items-start gap-2.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-cream-700)]">
              <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" class="mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-[var(--color-coral-500)]" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M18 6 6 18M6 6l12 12" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" />
              </svg>
              {fact}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    </CaptionedBlock>

    <PawTrail bg="bg-[var(--color-surface)]" colorClass="text-[var(--color-coral-300)]" />
  </div>

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Yorkie's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Yorkshire Terrier puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Yorkie explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about how our free home delivery and setup works.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm, warm and close. Tiny puppies chill easily under aircon, so a warm bed corner matters, along with a fixed feeding routine of regular small meals and the toilet pads where we placed them. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and the terrier turns up. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; see what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

